c</i> ‘cock, bird’), a type of bird that is notoriously easy to catch. Therefore, the name might have been either for a person who caught or sold woodcock, or a nickname for a gullible person.","in some cases, because there can be confusion between <i>-cock</i> and <i>-cot</i> in surnames, and therefore the name may also be a variant of <b>Woodcott</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, shelter’, such as Woodcott in Cheshire and Hampshire or Woodcote in Hampshire, Surrey, Oxfordshire, Warwickshire, and Shropshire, or from any residence at a cottage in or near a wood."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodcox","meanings":["English: variant of   Woodcock  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":34,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Woodcock was born in 1421, in Lancashire, England, his father, Seth Woodcock, was 31 and his mother, Mrs. Seth Woodcock, was 27. He married Alison Livesey in 1446, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1466, in England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1421–1466":"1421–1466","1423–1506":"1423–1506","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1452–1522":"1452–1522","1390–1465":"1390–1465","1394–1423":"1394–1423","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","after 1423":"pärast 1423","1426":"1426","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1423":"1423","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1465":"1465","1452":"1452","Abt. 1452":"umbes 1452","1506":"1506","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1421–1466":"1421–1466","1423–1506":"1423–1506","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","1452–1522":"1452–1522","1390–1465":"1390–1465","1394–1423":"1394–1423","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","after 1423":"1423 jälkeen","1426":"1426","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1423":"1423","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1465":"1465","1452":"1452","Abt. 1452":"noin 1452","1506":"1506","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1421–1466":"1421–1466","1423–1506":"1423–1506","1426–Female":"1426–Décédée","1452–1522":"1452–1522","1390–1465":"1390–1465","1394–1423":"1394–1423","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","after 1423":"après 1423","1426":"1426","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1423":"1423","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1465":"1465","1452":"1452","Abt. 1452":"environ 1452","1506":"1506","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire,